//check connection
if ($conn->connect_error) {
    die("Connection failed: " . $conn->connect_error);
} 

Make sure to replace the values for $host, $username, $password, and $dbname with your own database connection information.

Step 3: Execute SQL Queries

Now that you have a connection to the database, you can execute SQL queries using PHP. Here's an example:
$sql = "SELECT * FROM users";
$result = $conn->query($sql);

if ($result->num_rows > 0) {
    // output data of each row
    while($row = $result->fetch_assoc()) {
        echo "id: " . $row["id"]. " - Name: " . $row["name"]. " - Email: " . $row["email"]. "<br>";
    }
} else {
